Verification Technology
As the numbers of nuclear weapons decrease, any uncertainties in the arsenals of other 
AND
sensitive information (restricted data) relating to nuclear weapon design or manufacturing.
The verification challenges are many:
• First: determine the requirements to verify inventories of special nuclear material, production capabilities, and numbers of weapons;
• Second: assess the state of technology necessary to meet those requirements;
• Third: develop any needed science and technology (S%26T);
• Fourth: determine whether that S%26T could reveal information that would compromise U.S. national security;
• And fifth: develop methods to protect the security of our assets.
A further challenge is to make certain the verification happens in a manner that does not reveal weapons details to non-nuclear weapon states as proscribed by Article I of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, or classified information reflecting national security interests and controlled through relevant U.S. laws and regulations.4
Recent monitoring and inspection practices affecting the United States and Russia focused on verifying the 
